WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified body profile for Panasonic cinema and hybrid cameras recording
in V-Log and V-Log L. It contains the exact mathematical IDT, V-Log and
V-Log L curve parameters with their inverses, native V-Gamut color space
primaries, white balance presets, ISO sensitivity ranges including Dual
Native ISO, and sensor metrology data for the Lumix S and GH series. This
is the single source of truth for linearizing Panasonic V-Log footage to
scene-referred ACES2065-1.

WHY IT EXISTS
Panasonic's V-Log and V-Gamut are designed to encode the full dynamic range
of their sensors (14+ stops) in a compact wide gamut. Integrating Panasonic
footage into an ACES or GIOP pipeline requires exact inverse V-Log and
V-Gamut-to-ACES matrix. Without this certified body file, users face
ambiguity between V-Log (full) and V-Log L (limited range), and the
V-Gamut primaries may be incorrectly mapped to Rec.2020. This file
provides the mathematically auditable IDT for all Panasonic log variants.

HOW IT WORKS
The file defines the transform chain:
  1. Inverse V-Log or V-Log L (piecewise log) → linear V-Gamut RGB.
  2. V-Gamut to ACES2065-1 matrix (3x3, D65-to-D60 adaptation).
  3. White balance gain inverse (as-shot or preset).
Separate constants are provided for V-Log (full range) and V-Log L
(0-1 normalized limited range).

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- DaVinci Resolve (via DCTL or OCIO config)
- Nuke (via Python API or STMap)
- Baselight (BLG stack)
- Any ACES-compliant grading or compositing tool.

WHO USES IT
- L2 GIOP Engineers: implement the IDT in pipeline tools.
- L3 GIOP Colorists: verify correct linearization before grading.
- DITs and editors handling Panasonic Lumix original footage.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Replaces the Panasonic Varicam LUT dependency with an open, auditable
mathematical transform. Resolves the V-Log vs V-Log L ambiguity by
providing both sets of constants. Ensures that V-Gamut, not Rec.2020,
is used as the source primaries, preventing hue shifts in highly
saturated colors. Validates Dual Native ISO metadata for correct
noise profiling.

