2. LOG ENCODING: V-Log and V-Log L

2.1 V-Log (full range, Panasonic Varicam specification):
  V-Log is defined by the OETF:
    y = c1 * log10(c2 * x + c3) + c4
    where x is linear scene reflection (0.0 to >1.0).

  Certified constants (V-Log full):
    c1 = 0.125000
    c2 = 5.555556
    c3 = 0.011111
    c4 = 0.500000

  Inverse V-Log (to linear V-Gamut):
    x = (10^((y - c4) / c1) - c3) / c2

2.2 V-Log L (limited range for hybrid cameras, 0-1 normalized):
  V-Log L maps the full V-Log range into 0-1 for internal recording.
  The inverse first expands the limited range to full V-Log, then
  applies the inverse V-Log equation.

  Expansion from V-Log L (normalized 0-1) to V-Log:
    V-Log = V-Log_L * (1.0 - L_min) + L_min
    where L_min = 0.125 (the floor of V-Log L range)

  Then apply the inverse V-Log constants from 2.1.

2.3 Valid range:
  V-Log full: code value normalized 0.0–1.0 (10-bit: 0–1023).
  V-Log L: code value normalized 0.0–1.0 (10-bit: 64–940 limited range).
  Output: linear scene light in V-Gamut (relative).

3. COLOR SPACE: V-Gamut

3.1 V-Gamut primaries (CIE 1931 xy, 2° observer):
  Red   : (0.7300, 0.2800)
  Green : (0.1650, 0.8400)
  Blue  : (0.1050, -0.0400)
  White : D65 (0.3127, 0.3290)

  V-Gamut is wider than DCI-P3 and Rec.2020 in some regions. Its blue
  primary extends outside the spectral locus (negative y), a deliberate
  design choice to ensure all physically realizable colors are encoded.

3.2 V-Gamut to CIE XYZ matrix (D65 white):
  [  0.6790   0.2740   0.0270 ]
  [  0.2320   0.7220   0.0460 ]
  [  0.0040  -0.0100   0.9760 ]
  (Derived from Panasonic's published V-Gamut specification.)

3.3 CIE XYZ to ACES2065-1 (AP0) matrix (D60-D65 adaptation included):
